          "body": "Verses 12-17 are the chapter's moral core, and they are arresting in their specificity. Job names four classic categories of the vulnerable (poor, fatherless, dying, widow) and three modes of engagement: delivery (29:12), joy-making (29:13), and active combat (29:17). He clothed himself in righteousness and justice (29:14) — the two standard Old Testament terms for ethical integrity, tsedeq and mishpat. He was eyes to the blind and feet to the lame (29:15) — replacing the missing capacity entirely, not supplementing it. He was a *father* to the needy (29:16) — relational, not merely institutional. And he investigated cases he did not know (29:16) — proactive justice, seeking out hidden injustice rather than waiting for it to surface. Most striking of all, he 'broke the jaws of the wicked and snatched the prey from his teeth' (29:17) — the language of violent intervention against a predator. Job was not a passive philanthropist. His righteousness was muscular, confrontational, and costly. Peter Davids notes the parallel to the New Testament's vision of the believing community as advocates for the poor (James 1:27; 2:14-17); Job's portrait is the Old Testament's fullest individual embodiment of that ethic."
