          "title": "The expectation that was not fulfilled — the nest, the root, the bow",
          "body": "Verses 18-20 are the chapter's most painful pivot: Job's former confidence about his future. He thought he would die in his nest — the bird's nest being the image of secure, natural, undisturbed death in one's own place. He expected his days to multiply like the sand — the patriarchal formula of dying old and full of days (Genesis 25:8). His root would spread to water (sustained organic vitality), dew would rest on his branch (nightly refreshment), his glory would be ever new, his bow renewed (continued strength and warrior-readiness). Every image is organic, sustained, naturally flourishing. Not one of these expectations has been fulfilled. He did not die in his nest — he is sitting on an ash heap (2:8). His days have not multiplied — they have become days of torment (30:17). His root has not spread to water — his body is dried up (30:30). The gap between expectation and reality is the theological question Job cannot answer and the friends' theology cannot accommodate."
